[QUOTE]Originally posted by RageFactor:<BR><STRONG>[QUOTE]Originally posted by Daimyo Wildfyre:<BR>[qb]Here's the bottom line. The way raids work, not every class can be useful. </STRONG><P>"Depends on what you fight just like anything else.  Sometimes you had better have a few pet classes with you when you go to raid.  Sometimes you better have a massive doter on hand.  Sometimes you had better have crowd control, other times you better have a fierce damage shield.  More often than not you had better have an fd puller."  <P>Ever been on a raid Rage? High lvl raids are all about efficiency... This dosen't mean that paladins and mages can't get into a raid but if the slot could be filled by a Warrior or Wizard and one is available, in almost every circumstance they will get invited to go before you... You still are usefull on a raid because every little bit counts...Oh, and you will never see a pet on a raid. As Daimyo the wise stated (who has been on a few raids in his time, I mean he is lvl 60 is he not?) pet's get people killed on raids, One of the reasons mage's and necro's are almost worthless on plane raids... Crowd control isn't that necissary because if the puller gets a few add's there are more than enough groups there to take care of them. <P>"This is just common sense.  You generalized too much when saying on raids.  The point is there is no, we had better have a paladin type raid."  <P>Of course there isn't... Never will be... Raids are about efficiency... Best tanks, healers, dd and melee dmg  dealers are the most efficient at their tasks... Because of this they are more needed.<P><STRONG>On a raid, all that matters is dealing damage and healing damage. That's really it.</STRONG><P>"That is BASICALLY what it comes down to, but what is the formula for this?  What makes it so that healing and dealing damage is most efficient?" <P>A group on any dragon raid should have at least 1 Cleric in the group and 1 backup healer. The rest of the slots are filled in with pure melee second and anything else the organizer could get s/he hands on third.<P><STRONG>Crowd control doesn't matter, buffs don't make a huge difference except for resist-type buffs, and utility means dick.</STRONG><P>"Never lead a raid.  EVER!  You have no idea how silly you sound.  Yes on some raids Crowd control is near impossible but other raids it is a pure necessity.  Utility buffs mean nothing?  *LOLOL*  Your main tank is dead in two hits then and when the mobs are through with him who do they go after next?"<P>Sure every bit helps. Its always good to have a few necro's to cast DMF on the party when doing naggy to avoid the lava but thats just about all you need in terms of utility spells on a naggy raid... About crowd control? I already said something about that... On large raids there are enough groups to deal with the add's the puller gets.<P><STRONG> All that matters is killing the bad guy as fast as possible witgh as few casualties as possible.</STRONG><P>"Hate to tell you this but if you aren't using the buffs and pets and such 9 times out of 10 (if you even kill the mob) you are most certainly not killing the guy as fast as possible and you certainly are having plenty of casualties."<P>There are always a few casualties on a raid... Can't be avoided. But there would be a hell of alot more casualties if someone allowed a mage or necro to summon a pet on a raid. Buffs help but not that much when your tanks dont last more than a few seconds against the mob without defensive disc.<P><STRONG> And that means Warriors, rogues, wizards, and clerics.</STRONG><P>"You named the MOST useful but to say that others never have a use in a big raid is just plain silly.  Their argument is not the same and never should ever be thought of in remotely the same way."<P>Effeciency... Warriors, Rogues, Wizards, Clerics are the most efficient at their tasks... Everyone else is CannonFodder(Which is a large part of the raid, you always need warm bodies there to keep mob from hitting the main dmg dealers and healers in the fight)
