<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
Jesus, where do I start.<P>Rage: We are talking about a couple of different things, so let me clarify what I meant by my earlier statements.<P>By "Raid," I mean the real, full-scale fight against the BOSS MOB. I mean the guild who's fought their way up Velk's lab, and is prepping for the fight with the big boy himself. I mean the guild who's planning to kill Trakanon in 15 minutes. I mean the guild who broke into Sleepers and means to have a go at Kerafyrm.<P>On these raids, there are two things that matter.<BR>1. Killing the bad guy.<BR>2. Keeping as many good guys alive.<P>To do this, we need a few things.<BR>1. Damage Source--warriors, rogues, monks, wizards<BR>2. Healer source--clerics, sometime shamans, druids<BR>3. Utility--Buffs from chanters, shamans, druids; Crowd control; DMF (for naggy); other case-specific buffs.<P>Line by line:<BR>"Druids can't do any damage? Since when? They get nukes plus they have resist buffs and THAT is what will save your life. "<BR>**Druid nukes don't land on uber mobs. Generally speaking, druids don't get to nuke on raids, since they're usually placed as a primary healer in a caster group. They heal and they buff. That's it.**<P>"Most mobs that are incredible hard to kill are mobs with a dangerous AE of some kind and resistance is what saves you from it. "<BR>**Druids aren't the only class that come with nice resist buffs. Clerics have decent ones as well--and person by person, a cleric is a lot more useful and important than a druid is.**<P>"Your argument was an isolated incidence, I am talking about a paladins entire career. "<BR>**My argument was that paladins aren't especially useful on raids. No doubt. This does not mean that paladins are useless in day-to-day groups. Paladins make superb secondary tanks, along with Shadowknights. Whether they make good enough tanks is a topic for another thread. Who's talking about an isolated incident?**<P>"Depends on what you fight just like anything else. Sometimes you had better have a few pet classes with you when you go to raid. Sometimes you better have a massive doter on hand. Sometimes you had better have crowd control, other times you better have a fierce damage shield. More often than not you had better have an fd puller. "<BR>**Unfortunately, pet classes are usually not a good thing. I can think of no true uber raid where pets are necessary, and a number where pets get the whole raid party killed. Massive DoTs are OUTLAWED on raids because in the past they have caused corpses to poof. Therefore, they are not allowed, even though VI claims to have fixed the problem. Crowd control is often useful, no doubt. But it isn't crucial to the epic fight against the BOSS MOB itself.**<P>"The point is there is no, we had better have a paladin type raid. "<BR>**There is no "we better have a _insert_the_following_ type raid, either: <BR>1. Shadowknight.<BR>2. Druid.<BR>3. Necromancer.<BR>4. Ranger.<BR>5. Magician.<BR>6. Rogue.<BR>7. Shaman.<P>The point is, the only classes that are UNIVERSALLY necessary on raids are warriors and clerics. Wizards are usually useful, as are monks for pulling. Only a VERY FEW CLASSES ARE ESSENTIAL FOR A RAID. And granted, paladins aren't one of them. There is a difference between essential and useful. All classes are useful, some are less useful than others.**<P>"Never lead a raid. EVER! You have no idea how silly you sound. Yes on some raids Crowd control is near impossible but other raids it is a pure necessity. Utility buffs mean nothing? *LOLOL* Your main tank is dead in two hits then and when the mobs are through with him who do they go after next?"<BR>**I led the first raid into Sleeper's on Fennin. I led the first raid into VP. I led the first raids on Naggy and Vox. I have led more raids than you have likely been on. On some raids, CC is important, agreed--but at the actual moment of the BOSS MOB fight, it is worthless. By "Utility," I mean what hybrids, druids, shamans, and others have have--utility in their ability to perform many different tasks with some degree of profiency, but not as well as the pure class can. Raids are always about efficency, and that means having the job done by the class made to do that job.**<P>"Hate to tell you this but if you aren't using the buffs and pets and such 9 times out of 10 (if you even kill the mob) you are most certainly not killing the guy as fast as possible and you certainly are having plenty of casualties."<BR>**You use a pet against Yelinak, Kerafyrm, Zlandicar, Klandicar, Dracoliche, or any of the other viciously powerful dragons that are running around in Norrath right now, the raid can get destroyed. A feared pet in PoF is the most dangerous thing you can have. A feared pet in ToV is even worse. A feared pet in Necropolis isn't real good, either.<BR>I am also aware that resist buffs are good. When did I ever say that resist buffs were useless?**<P>"You named the MOST useful but to say that others never have a use in a big raid is just plain silly. Their argument is not the same and never should ever be thought of in remotely the same way."<BR>**Isn't that exactly what YOU are arguing? hat paladins never have a use on a big raid? Neither do SK's, Rangers, Necromancers, and others. What I said was, raids demand efficiency. Hybrids are not efficient, they are not the best at what they do. Druids, similarly, are not the best at anything they do--except possibly resist buffing.**<P>"Aren't as powerful? Man, maybe your warrior has some bad luck with crits because my roomate crits a lot and very hard and if e turns that disc on, well..."<BR>**A big part of LH and HT is the fact that they are triggered. I can't guarantee that if I'm fighting and NEED that crit to survive, it'll happen. Nine times out of ten, it doesn't. LoH works as soon as you need it to. Harm Touch likewise. Yeah, my crits probably end up adding more damage than Harm Touch does. So what? I'm supposed to do melee damage. The SK's spells and pet combined easily overcome any advantage I have from crits. Any warrior that uses the crit discipline on a raid should be SHOT. Defensive is the absolute necessity on any raid.<P>"Every 30 swings you say? More like every 22-25 but we'll say 30"<BR>**30 was generous. Let's say 45.**<P>"Do you know what I do every 30 swings? swing again, no matter what I fight. Spells you say? Clerics are always there so technically my usefullness there is neutralized. What am I left with? A weaker defense because the AC on my items being lower than a warriors and a mediocre fighting ability because my weaps are weaker and so am I."<BR>**Clerics negate only your buffs. You can still heal yourself and others--just cuz the cleric does it better doesn't invalidate your own ability. You have access to weapons that are every bit as spectacular as a warriors'. The primal 2handers out of Sleeper's are a perfect example. The fact that you cannot duel wield simply means you do slightly less damage, which is at it should be.**<P>"Listen for a minute. I'll tell you this just so that you know. Not every raid is the same. "<BR>**Very true. But most raids require a certain small core of classes that changes very little. I can't think of any raid where a necro, SK, Pally, rogue, Druid, Magician, Bard is an absolute necessity. Obviously they make it easier. But they are not required for the raid to be a success. Clerics and warriors, usually monks and enchanters as well, often wizards--they are the absolute and only necessities.**<P>"What about to save the mana of main healers? Shamans and druids have the same amount of mana and their heals are very close. "<BR>**Shaman and druid heals don't hold a candle to clerics, especially on tanks. CH is the absolute most powerful weapon (figuratively speaking) in a healer's arsenal. Shamans and druids don't have CH.**<P>"I also ask that you never lead an important raid ever."<BR>**Refer to the above.**<P>"The point is that there are circumstances in which EVERY class(with the exception of the paladin) will be looked for in some situation. "<BR>**Wrong. SK's are never a necessity. Nor are necromancers. Nor are rogues. Nor are druids. Very few classes are REQUIRED in a particular raid situation.**<P>"No, stupid people get people killed, especially stupid people with pets. "<BR>**Stupid or not, a feared pet in Hate, Fear, Necropolis, ToV, or Sleeper's gets the raid killed.**<P>"Actually, adds can be the entire reason why your raid fails. Again depends on various factors. "<BR>**Complete agreement. But when I said crowd control didn't matter, I was referring to the BOSS MOB fight itself.**<P>"Going from 3000k hit points to 5000k hit points is going to help a great deal. Having a fire resist of 100 rather than 30 is going to help a great deal against AE fire. Having your meleers hasted and stred and raising there attacks matters because you are doing that much more damage faster. "<BR>**Already mentioned clerics. We all know HP is good. If ANYONE is ever on a dragon raid I'm leading without the appropriate unbuffed resists at 75, I remove them from the raid. They are a liability in that case, and they don't come.**<P>"can we say FEAR RAID? break groups always eveac out, "<BR>**There are a number of ways to break Fear. That's one of the worst.**<P>"Druids are second best blasters in game, 1012 DD ice/fire spells, i cant think of any other class with a DD of that caliber, "<BR>**Wildfire does 1024 damage. There is no ice-based equivalent of that damage caliber. Mages, at every spell circle up to that one (58, I believe) have better and mroe efficent dd.**<P>These are my thoughts. Respond if you wish.<P>--------------------<P>Do you know pain?<BR>Do you know rage?<BR>Do you know power?<P>Then that is all you need know of me.
